data: {"item":{"content":[{"annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"Let \\(p>3\\) be prime.\n\n1. Since \\(p\\) is a prime greater than \\(3\\), it is not divisible by \\(2\\) or \\(3\\).\n\n2. Because \\(p\\) is not divisible by \\(2\\), \\(p\\) is odd.  \n   Write \\(p=2k+1\\). Then\n   \\[\n   p^2=(2k+1)^2=4k^2+4k+1=4k(k+1)+1.\n   \\]\n   Among two consecutive integers \\(k\\) and \\(k+1\\), one is even, so \\(k(k+1)\\) is even. Hence \\(4k(k+1)\\) is divisible by \\(8\\), and therefore\n   \\[\n   p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{8}.\n   \\]\n\n3. Because \\(p\\) is not divisible by \\(3\\), its residue mod \\(3\\) must be \\(1\\) or \\(2\\), i.e. \\(p\\equiv \\pm1 \\pmod{3}\\). Squaring gives\n   \\[\n   p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{3}.\n   \\]\n\n4. So \\(p^2\\) is congruent to \\(1\\) both mod \\(8\\) and mod \\(3\\). Since \\(\\gcd(8,3)=1\\), this means\n   \\[\n   p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{\\operatorname{lcm}(8,3)}= \\pmod{24}.\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, for every prime \\(p>3\\), \\(\\boxed{p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{24}}\\).","type":"output_text"}],"id":"","phase":"final_answer","role":"assistant","status":"completed","type":"message"},"output_index":1,"sequence_number":483,"type":"response.output_item.done"}

event: response.completed
data: {"response":{"background":false,"completed_at":1776601224,"created_at":1776601212,"error":null,"frequency_penalty":0,"id":"","incomplete_details":null,"instructions":null,"max_output_tokens":4096,"max_tool_calls":null,"metadata":{},"model":"gpt-5.4-2026-03-05","object":"response","output":[{"encrypted_content":"","id":"","summary":[{"text":"**Structuring mathematical reasoning**\n\nI’m considering the implication that since p is not divisible by 3, it follows that p ≡ ±1 mod 3. This means p² ≡ 1 mod 3. Given that the greatest common divisor (gcd) of 8 and 3 is 1, p² leaves a remainder of 1 mod both numbers, thus leaving a remainder of 1 mod 24, calculated through the least common multiple (lcm). It's essential to respect the request for a clear reasoning structure before reaching the final conclusion. Let's keep it concise!","type":"summary_text"}],"type":"reasoning"},{"content":[{"annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"Let \\(p>3\\) be prime.\n\n1. Since \\(p\\) is a prime greater than \\(3\\), it is not divisible by \\(2\\) or \\(3\\).\n\n2. Because \\(p\\) is not divisible by \\(2\\), \\(p\\) is odd.  \n   Write \\(p=2k+1\\). Then\n   \\[\n   p^2=(2k+1)^2=4k^2+4k+1=4k(k+1)+1.\n   \\]\n   Among two consecutive integers \\(k\\) and \\(k+1\\), one is even, so \\(k(k+1)\\) is even. Hence \\(4k(k+1)\\) is divisible by \\(8\\), and therefore\n   \\[\n   p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{8}.\n   \\]\n\n3. Because \\(p\\) is not divisible by \\(3\\), its residue mod \\(3\\) must be \\(1\\) or \\(2\\), i.e. \\(p\\equiv \\pm1 \\pmod{3}\\). Squaring gives\n   \\[\n   p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{3}.\n   \\]\n\n4. So \\(p^2\\) is congruent to \\(1\\) both mod \\(8\\) and mod \\(3\\). Since \\(\\gcd(8,3)=1\\), this means\n   \\[\n   p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{\\operatorname{lcm}(8,3)}= \\pmod{24}.\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, for every prime \\(p>3\\), \\(\\boxed{p^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{24}}\\).","type":"output_text"}],"id":"","phase":"final_answer","role":"assistant","status":"completed","type":"message"}]